{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Student answers will vary.","teacherTip":"Take time to engage students in the topic by discussing their personal experiences. 

Ask students to describe their experiences and the impacts they observed.  If you are in a wildfire prone area, be aware that some students may have experienced significant loss and trauma.

For tips on discussing natural hazards from a personal and social perspective, please see our guide to <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tfQwtEKcYSlyCGl50DG_E7h1TmNjDqAiLmQWVUte8O4/edit?usp=sharing">Addressing Socioscientific Issues in the Classroom</a>.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Answers will vary.

Some years may have more acres burned because there is higher drought, which is a main factor in whether or not a wildfire will start. There may have been a greater effort to stop fires in some years compared to others as well. More precautions against fires may have been taken after a really bad fire season the year before.
","teacherTip":"If students are struggling with this question, help them realize that even though the trend in acres burned is increasing, there are some years that are lower than others. There are even consecutive years where the burned area has decreased every year. But overall, the burnt area is still much higher than it used to be.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Answers will vary.

Yes, there are groups of people that are more at risk when wildfires grow close to a city. Those with breathing issues will be impacted by the smoke in the air. Those who are too sick and unable to move easily are also at higher risk because it is much harder for them to evacuate. Also, people who live on the outskirts of the city, surrounded by trees and vegetation are more vulnerable to wildfires than people in the middle of the city. People who have less money may not be able to afford to evacuate or have access to transportation. Lastly, emergency workers who are necessary to fight the fire and take care of people injured in the fire cannot leave.","teacherTip":"Students may recognize the socio-economic status can play a role in wildfire risk. Some people can afford to evacuate and some cannot. Consider discussing this with students more deeply at the end of this activity. Discussion points are listed on the next page. 

For tips on discussing natural hazards from a personal and social perspective, please see our guide to <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1tfQwtEKcYSlyCGl50DG_E7h1TmNjDqAiLmQWVUte8O4/edit?usp=sharing">Addressing Socioscientific Issues in the Classroom</a>.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

