{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The goal of this activity is to have students **investigate the role that different factors play in wildfire spread**. Students will use the Wildfire Explorer model and work with variables like moisture content (drought level), wind speed and direction, and topography (slope of terrain) and compare both how fast wildfires spread and how many acres they cover. 

Students will use the model to set up different “controlled” experiments. Students place sparks under different conditions and begin to develop ideas about how each variable changes the outcome of the fire. For example, the more water in the system, the more moisture plants have and the slower they are to burn. Students will be able to relate each variable in the model to the Fire Triangle. Once students explore each variable, they will be asked to apply their understanding to a real-world case study: the Camp Fire in California. 
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"teacherTip","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"**The Wildfire module includes a real-time Class Dashboard, which you can launch from the STEM Resource Finder.** 

You can use the Class Dashboard (<a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1C_6hiZzdSF_p6edhJeY_q_SvulFEPlawo7OKSaF7E88/edit?usp=sharing" target="_blank">dashboard instructions</a>) to quickly assess students' understanding. 

In this activity, students will begin using the Wildfire Explorer model and taking snapshots of their model after running different experiments. You can see your students' snapshots in the Class Dashboard.","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"diggingDeeper","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":false,"content":"Ask students to do some research on where in the United States these types of landscapes are found. In fact, these types of landscapes can be found in almost every state in the U.S.

Begin to have students think about how fires in these areas may behave differently. The video, at 0:33, shows the three types of landscapes and the fires they support are very different. Ask students why they think that is. It is one of the concepts we will address in this activity.  
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"This is the first time students will have a chance to use the Wildfire Explorer model. 

To begin, students will experiment with drought level. They can start with the currently set-up model, or change the drought level by opening the **Terrain Setup** box by clicking the button in the bottom toolbar. The color of the zone will change based on the drought level selected.

This is also a good time to remind students of how to conduct a good scientific investigation. *To investigate the effect that a certain variable has on fire spread, they should only change one variable at a time.* For the drought level investigation, students should only change drought level and then make their observations.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"stickyNote"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"The more slope an environment has, the faster a fire will spread (given all other conditions are the same). This is because fire can preheat the fuels upslope, drying them out and making them more likely to burn. 

","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Depending on where students place the spark, the initial spread may not obviously show which terrain causes fire to spread the fastest. Encourage students to run the model for long periods of time, and to run multiple experiments and change the location of the sparks. Once they do this, the pattern should become clear.
","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Student answers will vary.

Students may think that a fire travels faster downhill because they may be thinking about balls rolling uphill versus downhill.
","teacherTip":"If students are uncertain about how the terrain or the starting location of the spark affects the spread of a wildfire, encourage them to continue using the model to solidify their understanding.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"discussionPoints","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"Ask students to relate this experiment to the Wildfire Explorer.

How does the experiment help them think about why fire spreads differently uphill compared to downhill?

","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The goal of this activity is to explore why wildfires are getting larger, specifically **how the amount and type of vegetation affects the spread of a wildfire**. Until this point we have not talked about the different fuel types. In this activity, students consider if and how a wildfire behaves differently when fueled with different vegetation. Of course, in a wildfire system, it is not possible to consider fuel type alone. Students will also need to think about the relationship between fuel type and moisture content. With less rainfall and hotter temperatures, the quantity of dried fuel for wildfires has risen.

Wildfires are particularly complicated when we start to factor in people. In this activity, we pay close attention to how the public policy of **wildfire suppression** has left a large amount of fuel in forests to burn. In this activity, students are asked to reason about multiple variables affecting the spread and intensity of wildfires. In addition, they are asked to consider the human role and how short-term actions (fire suppression) connect to the impact that wildfires can have on people and their communities. In the last activity in this module, they will consider longer-term actions (climate change).
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Answers will vary. 

Encourage students to go back and run the model to look closely for fire intensity in the fire front. Ask them about the different characteristics of the vegetation types again, like the size, moisture level, and density of the fuels.

For those who are very certain, encourage them to explore a wide variety of environmental conditions that cause low intensity or high intensity fires. The can adjust the wind, location of sparks, and types of vegetation in each zone to gain a deeper understanding of environmental conditions that affect fire intensity.","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"diggingDeeper","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"Some fires become so intense that they move from tree top to tree top. These are called crown fires. Share this webpage with your students. They can click and drag in the video and watch as the fire moves through the forest.

https://www.nist.gov/video/360deg-video-crown-fire-during-prescribed-burn-new-jersey-pine-barrens-march-27-2019
","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"This is a tough question, and the time scale students think about will affect their answer. Either answer can be backed up with good reasoning.","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"","teacherTip":"Use this question to start a discussion about the time scales and the availability of vegetation over time.

If students select yes, they are likely thinking in the short term, where fires will likely continue to increase due to the availability of dry, dead fuel.

If students select no, they are likely thinking in the long term, where it is possible that all of the readily available fuel will be burned and fires will no longer be as intense.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Student responses will vary.

Yes, there are environmental conditions in which mitigation methods do not work. If the wind is very strong, the fire blows over the fire line like it isn’t even there. This is because embers from the advancing wildfire get blown past the fireline and start a fire on the other side. Also, if the vegetation is too dry, a helitack will not really work because the fire can dry out the fuels quickly again and burn them as it would have before.","teacherTip":"There is no one correct answer to this extension question. Rather, the goal is to generate student ideas that they will, hopefully, support with evidence from the model.

In the next activity, students will explore extreme drought conditions where  wildfires spread so quickly that they cannot be easily contained. This scenario represents what may happen as global temperatures continue to rise and certain areas of the country become drier.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"framing","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The goal of this final activity in the wildfire module begins by providing students with the opportunity to explore real-world climate change data.

Students will use the Wildfire Explorer to model wildfire spread during extreme droughts and explore the future of wildfire risks and impacts. The future of wildfire risk is quite complex. This activity introduces some concepts related to forest succession. As students reason through the future of wildfires, encourage them to include uncertainty when making predictions, which is a core practice used when predicting near-term and long-term outcomes.

By the end of this activity, students will be better able to answer the framing question: **How will wildfire risks and impacts change over the next 100 years?**","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"windowShade","windowShade":{"windowShadeType":"diggingDeeper","layout":"mediaLeft","initialOpenState":true,"content":"The current drought is of great concern for scientists. Have your students watch the following video, where scientists talk about past megadroughts and the current drought in the western United States.

https://yaleclimateconnections.org/2021/08/is-western-u-s-experiencing-a-megadrought/

How might a megadrought contribute to wildfire risks and impacts across the world in the near future? What if it lasted for several more decades?","content2":"","mediaType":"none","mediaCaption":"Last, First. "Title of Work." Year created. Site Title [OR] Publisher. Gallery [OR] Location. http://www.url.com.","mediaURL":""}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"Student answers will vary.

I was not able to contain the fire.  In many cases, the firelines I built were completely useless. The fire burned right over them without being slowed down at all. The helitacks were equally useless, as they did not cover enough area or slow down the fire enough to stop it from spreading. Both took too long to regenerate to be used again!
","teacherTip":"Students may have noticed earlier that fire lines are not always effective. They need to be drawn quickly. Under certain conditions such as when “extreme drought” is selected or when there are very high winds, the fire will burn right by fire lines. This simulates real world fire spread where wind can carry embers and fire can jump the gap in the vegetation that a fireline creates. In severe drought areas, this occurs frequently.","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}

{"tipType":"questionWrapper","questionWrapper":{"correctExplanation":"","distractorsExplanation":"","exemplar":"This risk map could change in a couple ways. First, there could be more risk surrounding the city because the fuels could be drier due to increased temperature and drought. More fuels would be ready to burn, and thus the risk of a wildfire occurring could be higher. There is a good chance more frequent or worse fires could occur.

On the other hand, if fires burn through this area in the next 100 years, it could reduce the amount of fuel left to burn and actually decrease the amount of area at high risk from wildfires. This could be compounded if development continues and more trees are knocked down, more roads are built, and more potential wildfire fuel is destroyed. 
","teacherTip":"","teacherTipImageOverlay":"","location":"bottom"}}
